hands_on_practices.solution:
We use the provided competitive ELISA model for absorbance versus competitor concentration:
$$A(C) = A_{min} + \frac{A_{max} - A_{min}}{1 + \frac{C}{\text{IC50}}}.$$
For a given data point with competitor concentration $C$ and measured absorbance $A$, solve for $\text{IC50}$ algebraically. Subtract $A_{min}$ and invert:
$$A - A_{min} = \frac{A_{max} - A_{min}}{1 + \frac{C}{\text{IC50}}}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
1 + \frac{C}{\text{IC50}} = \frac{A_{max} - A_{min}}{A - A_{min}}.$$
Thus,
$$\frac{C}{\text{IC50}} = \frac{A_{max} - A}{A - A_{min}}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\text{IC50} = C\,\frac{A - A_{min}}{A_{max} - A}.$$

Apply this to HSA (primary antigen) with $A_{max} = 1.800$, $A_{min} = 0.050$, $A = 0.650$, $C = 12.0$:
$$\text{IC50}_{\text{HSA}} = 12.0 \cdot \frac{0.650 - 0.050}{1.800 - 0.650}
= 12.0 \cdot \frac{0.600}{1.150}.$$
Writing decimals as fractions, $0.600 = \frac{3}{5}$ and $1.150 = \frac{23}{20}$, so
$$\text{IC50}_{\text{HSA}} = 12 \cdot \frac{\frac{3}{5}}{\frac{23}{20}}
= 12 \cdot \frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{20}{23}
= \frac{720}{115}
= \frac{144}{23}.$$

Apply the same to BSA (cross-reacting antigen) with $A = 0.925$, $C = 450.0$:
$$\text{IC50}_{\text{BSA}} = 450.0 \cdot \frac{0.925 - 0.050}{1.800 - 0.925}
= 450.0 \cdot \frac{0.875}{0.875}
= 450.0.$$

The cross-reactivity is defined as the dimensionless ratio
$$\text{CR} = \frac{\text{IC50}_{\text{HSA}}}{\text{IC50}_{\text{BSA}}}
= \frac{\frac{144}{23}}{450}
= \frac{144}{10350}
= \frac{8}{575}.$$
As a decimal, $\frac{8}{575} \approx 0.013913\ldots$, which rounded to three significant figures is $0.0139$.
